  "prompt": "Graph Theory: What does it mean if vertices are adjacent?",
  "response": "In **graph theory**, the term **adjacent vertices** (or **neighbors**) refers to two vertices that are connected directly by an edge. In simpler terms, if there is a single edge that links Vertex A to Vertex B, then Vertex A and Vertex B are considered adjacent to each other.\n\n### Formal Definition\n\n- **Adjacency**: In an **undirected graph**, two vertices \\( u \\) and \\( v \\) are **adjacent** if there exists an edge \\( \\{u, v\\} \\) connecting them.\n- In a **directed graph** (digraph), the concept is similar but direction matters:\n  - **Adjacent**: Vertex \\( u \\) is adjacent to vertex \\( v \\) if there is a directed edge from \\( u \\) to \\( v \\) (\\( u \\rightarrow v \\)).\n\n### Example\n\nConsider the following undirected graph:\n\n```\nA \u2014 B\n|   |\nC \u2014 D\n```\n\n- **Adjacent Pairs**:\n  - A and B (connected by an edge \\( \\{A, B\\} \\))\n  - A and C (connected by an edge \\( \\{A, C\\} \\))\n  - B and D (connected by an edge \\( \\{B, D\\} \\))\n  - C and D (connected by an edge \\( \\{C, D\\} \\))\n\n- **Non-adjacent Pairs**:\n  - A and D (no direct edge connecting them)\n  - B and C (no direct edge connecting them)\n\n### Properties Related to Adjacent Vertices\n\n1. **Degree of a Vertex**: The number of vertices adjacent to a given vertex. For example, in the graph above:\n   - Vertex A has a degree of 2 (adjacent to B and C).\n   - Vertex B also has a degree of 2 (adjacent to A and D).\n\n2. **Adjacent Edges**: Two edges are adjacent if they share a common vertex. For example, in the graph above:\n   - Edges \\( \\{A, B\\} \\) and \\( \\{A, C\\} \\) are adjacent because they both share vertex A.\n\n3. **Adjacency Matrix**: A way to represent a graph where each cell \\( (i, j) \\) indicates whether vertices \\( i \\) and \\( j \\) are adjacent.\n   - For an undirected graph without loops, the adjacency matrix is symmetric, and diagonal entries are typically 0.\n\n### Importance of Adjacency\n\nUnderstanding adjacency is fundamental in graph theory as it forms the basis for many concepts and algorithms, including:\n\n- **Graph Traversal**: Techniques like Depth-First Search (DFS) and Breadth-First Search (BFS) rely on exploring adjacent vertices.\n- **Pathfinding Algorithms**: Finding the shortest path between vertices involves traversing through adjacent vertices.\n- **Graph Coloring**: Assigning colors to vertices such that no two adjacent vertices share the same color.\n\n### Summary\n\n- **Adjacent vertices** are directly connected by an edge.\n- This concept is pivotal for analyzing the structure and properties of graphs.\n- Adjacency influences various algorithms and applications within graph theory.\n\nIf you have a specific context or additional questions about adjacency in graphs, feel free to ask!",
